    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "As noticed/commented in #858, #731, #210... (Neo)vim uses `garray_T` as a dynamic string data type and would benefit from a dedicated structure.\n\nAn ugly example of `garray_T` as a dynamic string can be found in `charset.c`:\n\n``` c\nchar_u* str_foldcase(char_u *str, int orglen, char_u *buf, int buflen)\n  FUNC_ATTR_NONNULL_RET\n{\n  garray_T ga;\n  int i;\n  int len = orglen;\n\n#define GA_CHAR(i) ((char_u *)ga.ga_data)[i]\n#define GA_PTR(i) ((char_u *)ga.ga_data + i)\n#define STR_CHAR(i) (buf == NULL ? GA_CHAR(i) : buf[i])\n#define STR_PTR(i) (buf == NULL ? GA_PTR(i) : buf + i)\n\n  // Copy \"str\" into \"buf\" or allocated memory, unmodified.\n  if (buf == NULL) {\n    ga_init(&ga, 1, 10);\n\n    ga_grow(&ga, len + 1);\n    memmove(ga.ga_data, str, (size_t)len);\n    ga.ga_len = len;\n  } else {\n    if (len >= buflen) {\n      // Ugly!\n      len = buflen - 1;\n    }\n    memmove(buf, str, (size_t)len);\n  }\n\n  if (buf == NULL) {\n    GA_CHAR(len) = NUL;\n  } else {\n    buf[len] = NUL;\n  }\n```\n\nWhat about using [`kstring.h`](https://github.com/attractivechaos/klib/blob/master/kstring.h) as a dynamic string library? We've been using `klib` for other structures, it's a non-opaque type (i.e. it's OK to use its fields directly as we do with `garray_T`) and has even less fields than `garray_T` (same size because `garray_T` uses `int` for the 4 length fields it has).\n",
